{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17992"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17992"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.81,0.07,0,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10706"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17992"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58597"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5373"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24929"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding the upper thresholds of benefits of exercise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["There is no risk of cardiovascular events with high-intensity exercise","Excessive exercise can increase the risk of musculoskeletal injuries","Exercising more than 150 minutes per week provides no additional health benefits","Moderate exercise is only beneficial for weight loss","Exercising more than 300 minutes per week is recommended for all adults"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive exercise can increase the risk of musculoskeletal injuries\u003C/strong\u003E. While regular physical activity is beneficial for health, there is a point at which excessive exercise can lead to negative outcomes, such as increased risk of injuries and cardiovascular events. It is important to balance exercise intensity and duration to avoid these risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercising more than 150 minutes per week\u003C/strong\u003E can provide additional health benefits, but the benefits may plateau or even become negative if exercise is excessive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere is a risk of cardiovascular events\u003C/strong\u003E with high-intensity exercise, especially in individuals with underlying heart conditions or those who are not accustomed to such levels of activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercising more than 300 minutes per week\u003C/strong\u003E is not universally recommended for all adults, as individual fitness levels and health conditions should be considered when determining exercise regimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModerate exercise\u003C/strong\u003E is beneficial for a variety of health outcomes, not just weight loss. It can improve cardiovascular health, mental well-being, and reduce the risk of chronic diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Regular physical activity is associated with numerous health benefits, including reduced risk of chronic diseases.","Excessive exercise can lead to negative health outcomes, such as increased risk of injury and cardiovascular events.","Moderate-intensity exercise is generally recommended for most adults to achieve health benefits."],"references":["Moghetti P, Bacchi E, Brangani C, Don\u00e0 S, Negri C. Metabolic Effects of Exercise. Front Horm Res. 2016;47:44-57. doi: 10.1159/000445156. Epub 2016 Jun 27. PMID: 27348753","Thyfault JP, Bergouignan A. Exercise and metabolic health: beyond skeletal muscle. Diabetologia. 2020 Aug;63(8):1464-1474. doi: 10.1007/s00125-020-05177-6. Epub 2020 Jun 11. PMID: 32529412; PMCID: PMC7377236","Keller J, Zackowski K, Kim S, Chidobem I, Smith M, Farhadi F, Bhargava P. Exercise leads to metabolic changes associated with improved strength and fatigue in people with MS. Ann Clin Transl Neurol. 2021 Jun;8(6):1308-1317. doi: 10.1002/acn3.51368. Epub 2021 May 6. PMID: 33955210; PMCID: PMC8164856","Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58597"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17992"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58597"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T04:07:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T21:16:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta